    rationale: "Pectus excavatum causes posterior depression of the lower sternum, which can physically compress the right ventricle and pulmonary outflow tract against the spine. This structural compression creates turbulent blood flow that produces a murmur without any intrinsic valvular pathology. The normal echocardiogram confirms the absence of valvular disease. Increased pulmonary vascular resistance from hypoxia is not the mechanism in an otherwise healthy adolescent. Mitral valve prolapse and aortic root dilation are separate conditions not caused by sternal depression.",
