    rationale: "In emphysema, destruction of alveolar walls eliminates the radial traction that normally holds small airways open. During exhalation, these unsupported airways tend to collapse (dynamic airway collapse), trapping air and causing hyperinflation. Pursed-lip breathing creates resistance at the mouth during exhalation, generating back-pressure (positive expiratory pressure) that is transmitted back to the small airways, keeping them open and allowing more complete exhalation. This reduces air trapping and improves gas exchange. It does not increase inspiratory flow, recruit inspiratory muscles, or activate the Hering-Breuer reflex.",
